</mj-text><mj-text margin="0" padding="0"><h3 style="padding:.3em;font-family:'Libre Franklin','Arial Black';font-weight:700;background-color:#fcd232;font-size:24px;text-align:center;">Breaking Trail</h3></mj-text><mj-text>

<h2>Advocates hope Colorado wolf reintroduction can include Mexican gray wolves</h2>

</mj-text><mj-image src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Mexican-geay-wolf-3.png?w=800" /><mj-text><p style="font-size:12px;font-family:'Libre Franklin',Arial,sans-serif;color:#727273;padding:0 12px;margin:0;"><em>A captive Mexican gray wolf photographed at the Sevilleta National Wildlife Refuge in New Mexico. Of 83 Mexican gray wolf pups bred in captivity and released into wild dens since 2016, only 13 have been documented surviving to breeding age. (Provided by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service)</em></span></p>

<blockquote class="wp-block-quote" style="width:90%;max-width:500px;border-left: 4px double #fcd232;padding: 0px 10px;padding: 0px 10px;margin-left:0;"><span style="font-size:1.2em;line-height:1.3em;font-family:Georgia,serif;font-weight:bold;">&#8220;Possibly even save it from extinction.&#8221;</span><br><br><span style="font-size:1em;"><em>— Colorado Parks and Wildlife Commissioner Jay Tuchton</em></span></blockquote>

</mj-text>
<mj-table>
	<tr style="border:2px solid white;">
	<td style="padding: 6px;text-align:center;font-size:22px;background-color:#fcd232;font-weight:bold;" width="40%">196</td><td style="font-size:14px;padding:12px;color:#000000;background-color:#DCEEF2;" width="60%">Number of Mexican gay wolves roaming New Mexico and Arizona, compared to 6,000 gray wolves in the U.S. Northern Rockies</td></tr>
</mj-table>
<mj-text>

<p>The Colorado Parks and Wildlife commission on Friday will get their first glimpse at a draft plan for reintroducing wolves to the Western Slope. The plan won&#8217;t include Mexican gray wolves, but a group of wildlife advocates are hoping that changes.</p>

<p>Colorado&#8217;s welcoming of wolves could be an opportunity to help a subspecies of wolf that has suffered while gray wolves in the north have thrived. If Colorado included Mexican gray wolves in its reintroduction effort, the state could &#8220;possibly even save it from extinction,&#8221; Colorado Parks and Wildlife Commissioner Jay Tutchton told Colorado Sun freelance journalist Elizabeth Miller.</p>

<p>Gray wolves and their Mexican cousins were exterminated from the Lower 48 in the early 1900s. Reintroduction efforts by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service launched in the 1990s have helped restore the predators to Western landscapes. There are about 6,000 gray wolves in the West but only about 196 Mexican gray wolves roaming New Mexico and Arizona.</p>

<p>They rank among the rarest of North America&#8217;s mammals.</p>

<p>&#8220;If you&#8217;re going to do a project like reintroduce wolves to Colorado, you might be doing a service to conservation if you introduce the rarer of the species,&#8221; Tutchton said.</p>

<p>There are a lot of reasons Mexican gray wolves have not been part of the initial reintroduction plan. A November 2021 report by the technical working group of scientists sculpting details of the Colorado reintroduction plan concluded the Mexican gray wolves were the least desirable choice of wolves to bring to Colorado, which is not historic habitat for the subspecies. But after a federal court overturned a 2020 decision to remove gray wolves from endangered species protections, both subspecies of wolves involve procedural challenges facing the capture and relocation of a federally protected animal.</p>

<p>Wolf advocates argue the two subspecies are not really that different. Adding a mix of Mexican gray wolves and gray wolves from the north to Colorado could open the possibility of a hybrid wolf that more closely resembles wolves that roamed the length of the Rocky Mountains centuries ago. And that&#8217;s got all kinds of downstream implications involving efforts to protect two distinct subspecies of wolves.</p>

<p>&#8220;Success is when the species is functioning as it did for thousands of years before we screwed things up,&#8221; Tutchton said.</p>

