</mj-text><mj-text margin="0" padding="0"><h3 style="padding:.3em;font-family:'Libre Franklin','Arial Black';font-weight:700;background-color:#fcd232;font-size:24px;text-align:center;">The Guide</h3></mj-text><mj-text>

<h2>Annual economic outlook report highlights outdoor recreation among state&#8217;s strongest industries</h2>

</mj-text><mj-image src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/RM_PlungeDay1_077.jpg?w=800" /><mj-text><p style="font-size:12px;font-family:'Libre Franklin',Arial,sans-serif;color:#727273;padding:0 12px;margin:0;"><em>Greg Wolfgang, the manager of the BLM's Grand Junction Field Office, descends a section of Palisade Plunge trail in September 2020. Recreation tourism in Mesa County — like visitors to the area&#8217;s renowned bike trails — creates a $556 million economic impact. (Joey Early, RockyMounts, Special to The Colorado Sun)</em></span></p>

</mj-text>
<mj-table>
	<tr style="border:2px solid white;">
	<td style="padding: 6px;text-align:center;font-size:22px;background-color:#fcd232;font-weight:bold;" width="40%">$11.6 billion</td><td style="font-size:14px;padding:12px;color:#000000;background-color:#DCEEF2;" width="60%">Outdoor recreation&#8217;s contribution to the Colorado economy in 2021</td></tr>
</mj-table>
<mj-text>

<p>A quick peek inside the annual<a target="_blank"  href="https://www.colorado.edu/business/sites/default/files/attached-files/2023_beof_book_final_120522_lr.pdf"> Colorado Business Economic Outlook</a> shows outdoor recreation as a beacon for growth.</p>

<p>The 2023 report — that <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2022/12/07/colorado-2023-economy-forecast-business-jobs/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email">Sun reporter Tamara Chuang wrote about this week</a> — projects a strengthening outdoor recreation economy in Colorado for 2023. Visits to federal public lands could reach a record 72.6 million. Visits to Colorado&#8217;s 43 state parks reached 20 million in 2022, up from 15 million in 2019. Skier visits reached <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2022/06/09/colorado-skier-visits-vail-resorts-2021-2022/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email">13.8 million in 2021-22</a>, an all-time high. And spending in Western Slope towns <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2022/12/01/colorado-harvest-record-sales-tax-revenue/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email">also set records</a>.</p>

<p>&#8220;People want to spend time in the outdoors and will spend money to do so,&#8221; reads the report.</p>

<p>Outdoor recreation contributed <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2022/11/10/outdoor-recreation-economy-federal-office/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email">$11.6 billion to the Colorado economy in 2021</a>, supporting 125,200 workers who earned $5.7 billion. This year&#8217;s outlook report detailed the nearly <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2022/04/04/conor-hall-outdoor-recreation-question/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email">year-long statewide tour</a> by the Outdoor Recreation Industry Office, which identified how all conversations around the outdoor recreation economy must include discussions about labor shortages, affordable housing and the impacts of climate change. Those challenges offer chances for unique collaborations that gather municipalities, counties and regions around recreational values.</p>

<p>&#8220;Strong advocates, dynamic collaborations, innovative educational programs, passionate entrepreneurs, and many other ecosystem constituents are taking outdoor recreation and community economic vitality to exciting new places,&#8221; the report reads.</p>

<p>The report&#8217;s highlighted communities illustrate the outsized impacts recreation and the outdoor industry have in rural communities. Mesa County, for example, has spent several years positioning itself as a headquarters for outdoor businesses and now counts 4,501 jobs at outdoor businesses that add $318 million in economic value to the county. Add in recreation tourism — which supports nearly 5,400 jobs and adds $556 million in spending — and the outdoor recreation economy supports about one in 10 jobs in Mesa County and stirs an $875 million economic impact, accounting for 7.5% of the county&#8217;s total economic activity.</p>

</mj-text><mj-text align="center" font-size="9px" padding="0px" color="#9a9a9a"> UNDERWRITTEN BY </mj-text><mj-image src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/KlahrBlueWhite.png" width="300px" href="https://cosun.co/3EtLqvx" target="_blank" padding="0px 0px 8px" /><mj-text>&nbsp;

