<h2>Never been a better era for backcountry safety tools … let&#8217;s use &#8217;em!</h2>

</mj-text><mj-image src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Richmond-Ridge-slide-Dec-7-1-1.png?w=800" /><mj-text><p style="font-size:12px;font-family:'Libre Franklin',Arial,sans-serif;color:#727273;padding:0 12px;margin:0;"><em>Skiers triggered this slide on Richmond Ridge near Aspen on Dec. 7.(Provided by Colorado Avalanche Information Center)</em></span></p>

<blockquote class="wp-block-quote" style="width:90%;max-width:500px;border-left: 4px double #fcd232;padding: 0px 10px;padding: 0px 10px;margin-left:0;"><span style="font-size:1.2em;line-height:1.3em;font-family:Georgia,serif;font-weight:bold;">&#8220;It can be easy to underestimate the current potential for avalanches.&#8221;</span><br><br><span style="font-size:1em;"><em>— Dec. 7 update from Colorado Avalanche Information Center</em></span></blockquote>

</mj-text>
<mj-table>
	<tr style="border:2px solid white;">
	<td style="padding: 6px;text-align:center;font-size:22px;background-color:#fcd232;font-weight:bold;" width="40%">53</td><td style="font-size:14px;padding:12px;color:#000000;background-color:#DCEEF2;" width="60%">Human-caused avalanches in Colorado in the first week of December</td></tr>
</mj-table>
<mj-text>

<p>The snowy start to the winter has resorts tickled as they open up new terrain and see holiday reservations rebound from fall reticence.</p>

<p>But it&#8217;s a challenging start to the avalanche season. Perusing the <a target="_blank"  href="https://avalanche.state.co.us/">new Colorado Avalanche Information Center website</a>, I count 53 human-caused avalanches in the state in the first week of December. Most of those were remotely triggered and controlled releases by skiers, but many were unintended. Already there are reports of backcountry skiers taking rides in slides.</p>

<p>This week&#8217;s storm elevated avalanche danger across the state, with first-of-the-season avalanche warnings in the southern San Juans and central Colorado&#8217;s Elk, West Elk and northwestern Sawatch ranges through Thursday. The new snow is piling deep on a weak layer that formed during that dry period in November and will challenge our snowpack through the season. As heavy new snow buries that persistent weak layer 2-, 3- or even 4-feet deep, CAIC pushed avalanche danger from moderate to high — 4 out of 5 — in two zones for Thursday.</p>

<p>Last season seven backcountry travelers were killed in avalanches in Colorado, down from a <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2021/10/27/colorado-avalanche-backcountry-fatalities-caic/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email">heartbreaking 12 in 2020-21</a>.</p>

<p>If this start to the winter is an indication of what&#8217;s to come and we see that summer trend of consistent moisture continuing through the spring, this will be a long and complicated avalanche season. Check your beacon batteries. Brush up your skills with an awareness clinic. And check the forecasts. The overhauled CAIC website offers deeper details into more specific zones.</p>

<p>There&#8217;s never been a better era for backcountry safety, with <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2021/10/27/colorado-avalanche-backcountry-fatalities-caic/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email">plenty of high-tech tools</a> and avalanche scientists supporting a rich well of digital resources. But nothing works without well-informed decision making in the backcountry. As they say, <a target="_blank"  href="https://avalanche.state.co.us/education/caic-programs/know-before-you-go-colorado">Know Before You Go</a>.</p>

<p><em>— j</em></p>

